    "This identifies behavioural patterns as cultural when they differ between geographically diverse groups of the same species.",
    "If genetic differences between these groups can be ruled out (e.g.",
    "because of inter-group migration), and behavioural differences cannot be attributed to local ecological conditions, then behavioural patterns are likely to be products of social learningand so are indicative of variant cultural traditions.",
    "While influential, this method has been criticized as insufficiently informative, and as resting on a conceptual problem, specifically a false dichotomy between nature and culture (Rogoff, 2003).",
    "First, it probably undercounts culture, where behaviours are universal (and so do not differ between populations) but are nonetheless socially learned."
